        Cold-call agent approaches and unsolicited offers in Brisbane: how sellers should evaluate them
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        An agent calls, doorknocks, or drops a letter claiming they have a buyer for your property. Most are routine prospecting; a few are genuine. Here is how to tell the difference and decide whether to engage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>You are not actively selling. The phone rings, or a printed letter lands in the mailbox, or someone knocks on the front door. It is a real estate agent. They claim to have a buyer for your property, or they suggest now is a great time to sell, or they make a direct off-market offer. The pitch is well rehearsed. The pressure is real but quiet. The question is what to do with the conversation.</p>

      <p>Most homeowners in Brisbane's inner east will receive several of these approaches each year, and many in tightly held streets will receive them every month. Almost all are pure prospecting. A small number reflect a genuine buyer who is willing to act. Telling the two apart matters because how you respond shapes whether you engage usefully, decline politely, or accidentally lock yourself into a result that under-performs the open market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is actually happening when an agent approaches you</h2>

      <p>Real estate agents prospect for listings constantly. It is part of the work, and the agents who do it consistently are usually the agents with the strongest local pipelines. In tightly held suburbs like Camp Hill, Bulimba, Morningside, Coorparoo, and Carindale, off-market and pre-market activity is common because stock is genuinely scarce. An agent contacting you might reflect any of three legitimate scenarios, or a fourth scenario that is far less flattering but more common than agents like to admit.</p>

      <p>The first scenario: the agent has a buyer who has missed out on similar properties and is willing to pay above market. This happens. It is less common than agents claim. When it is real, the buyer has usually been in the market for six to twelve months, has lost on three or four campaigns already, and has a clear price they will pay because they have done the comparable analysis themselves. The agent will be able to tell you specifics: which properties the buyer has bid on, what they paid in failed offers, what their pre-approval is set at. Vague claims about "a strong buyer" without specifics rarely hold up.</p>

      <p>The second scenario: the agent has been instructed by a developer or investor to source a specific block. This is most common in zones where knock-down-rebuild activity is active, where corner blocks or large flat sites have inherent value beyond the existing dwelling, or where adjoining-lot consolidation creates a development opportunity. If your block has these characteristics and you have noticed similar blocks in the area being acquired and rebuilt, this scenario is more plausible. The agent should be willing to tell you who the end buyer is, even if not by name then at least by type.</p>

      <p>The third scenario: the agent specialises in your suburb and is building a database of future-listing opportunities. This is the most common reality of cold-call approaches. The agent is not lying about wanting to help you sell; they are simply not telling you that no specific buyer exists right now. Their work is to be present in your suburb, to be the first call you make when you do decide to sell, and to convert that database into listings over time. There is nothing wrong with this approach, but it should not be confused with a genuine buyer-led offer.</p>

      <p>The fourth scenario, less common but real: the agent uses a vague claim about "a buyer" as a conversation opener, knowing the claim is unlikely to be challenged. The aim is to get into your home for an appraisal, gather information about your circumstances and motivations, and convert the relationship over months. If the buyer the agent referenced never materialises in any tangible way after the first conversation, this is what was happening.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask before engaging</h2>

      <p>The questions below filter the four scenarios quickly. An agent with a genuine buyer will answer them comfortably. An agent who is prospecting will become vague, change the subject, or pivot to "we should book an appraisal first."</p>

      <p>Is there a specific buyer, or are you prospecting for future listings? This is the most important question. Agents are required to answer it honestly. If the answer is anything other than a clear "yes, there is a specific buyer," treat the rest of the conversation as a relationship-building exercise rather than a transaction.</p>

      <p>What price has the buyer pre-approved or indicated? A genuine buyer with serious intent will have a finance position. The agent should be able to indicate the range, even if not the exact figure. "They are pre-approved up to $1.6m and have indicated they would pay above $1.5m for the right property" is a useful answer. "I would need to check" or "they are flexible on price" rarely is.</p>

      <p>What evidence in writing of the buyer's interest can you provide? A genuine buyer will have a written offer, a letter of interest, or a signed engagement with the agent. They will not be a verbal claim only. If the agent cannot provide anything written, the buyer either does not exist, is much earlier-stage than presented, or is willing to engage only if you are willing first.</p>

      <p>What is your recent track record selling in this exact suburb? An agent who has not sold in your suburb in the last six to twelve months is not the agent the genuine buyer would have asked to source the property. Local specialists handle local off-market activity. A generalist suburb-jumping agent claiming a local buyer should raise a flag.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The off-market sale tradeoff</h2>

      <p>An off-market sale avoids the cost of a marketing campaign and the disruption of open homes. It also avoids the price discovery that a campaign provides. These two effects are linked: the campaign is what creates competition between buyers, and competition between buyers is what drives final sale price toward the upper end of fair market value.</p>

      <p>Off-market deals in Brisbane's inner east typically achieve 5 to 10 per cent below what an open campaign produces. This is not a precise figure and varies by property type, suburb, and market conditions, but it is the broad pattern across the data. Occasionally the right buyer at the right time can match or beat campaign results, particularly when the buyer has missed out on three or four similar properties and is paying a "scarcity premium." But that scenario is the exception, not the rule.</p>

      <p>The decision about whether to accept an off-market offer is a tradeoff between certainty and price discovery. If the offer is strong, the timing suits, and the absence of a campaign is genuinely valuable to you (privacy, speed, avoiding the disruption of open homes during a personal circumstance), an off-market sale can be the right call. If the offer is merely acceptable and the campaign-versus-off-market price gap is likely to be 5 to 10 per cent, that gap on a $1.5m property is $75,000 to $150,000. That is not a number to leave on the table without a clear reason.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if the offer is interesting</h2>

      <p>Do not commit verbally on the call. There is no scenario in which you need to decide on the spot. Any agent who pressures you to commit verbally on the first conversation is running a tactic, not presenting a deal.</p>

      <p>Ask for the offer in writing. A serious buyer with a real number will produce something on paper. The act of asking filters out the prospecting calls quickly because there is nothing to put on paper.</p>

      <p>Compare the offer to recent comparable sales in your suburb. Pull the last six to twelve months of sales of similar properties on your street and within a few blocks. Ignore the asking prices and look only at the actual sale results. The offer you have received is informative only when read against this benchmark.</p>

      <p>Consult an agent of your choosing for a second opinion, with no obligation. A reputable local agent will give you a free appraisal and an honest read on whether the offer reflects fair value. If the offer turns out to be strong, you accept it. If the offer turns out to be 8 per cent below what a campaign would produce, you have data to negotiate with or to walk away.</p>

      <p>Consider whether a 7 to 14 day off-market exposure period would attract competing offers. A short, controlled off-market window allows your chosen agent to circulate the property quietly to known active buyers, generate competing offers, and create the price discovery that a single approach cannot. This is often a useful middle ground between accepting the cold-call offer and running a full campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if the approach is just prospecting</h2>

      <p>Thank the agent and decline politely. There is no need to be rude, and there is no need to apologise. Prospecting calls are a routine part of the agent's work; declining is a routine part of yours.</p>

      <p>If you might sell in the future, save their details. Their proactivity is a positive signal about their work ethic, and an agent who is consistently in your suburb is the agent most likely to know the buyers who matter when you do list. A short note in your contacts saves the conversation if you decide to interview them later.</p>

      <p>If you are not selling and have no interest in the relationship, ask them to remove your details from their contact list. You are entitled to do so under privacy law, and the request is straightforward to make. Reputable agents will comply on the first request.</p>

      <p>Do not feel pressured to engage. There is no "missed opportunity" cost to declining a cold-call approach. If a real buyer at a real price exists for your property today, the buyer's interest will not evaporate because you declined the first conversation. Genuine buyers who want a specific property come back through different channels until they secure it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to watch out for</h2>

      <p>High-pressure tactics ("we have a buyer right now, this offer expires today") are almost always tactics rather than reality. Genuine buyers in Brisbane's inner east do not impose 24-hour deadlines on owners who are not currently selling. The pressure is designed to short-circuit your decision-making, not reflect a real constraint.</p>

      <p>Vague claims about the buyer that resist verification are a warning sign. "An overseas family looking to relocate" or "a downsizer from the western suburbs" without any specifics that you can probe further on usually indicates the buyer is generic or notional rather than specific.</p>

      <p>The same agent contacting you every few months with the "same buyer" is a clear pattern of prospecting dressed as buyer-led activity. Genuine buyers transact and move on; they do not stalk a single property for six months while the agent keeps making the same call.</p>

      <p>Specific dollar figures that anchor you below market are a more sophisticated tactic. Agents with no genuine buyer sometimes quote artificially low numbers to lock in your expectations. The figure becomes your mental anchor, and the agent later proposes a campaign at that level claiming to "exceed expectations." If a quoted figure feels low against your own read of comparable sales, do not let it set your reference point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The privacy and contact angle</h2>

      <p>Many agents source contact details from public records, third-party databases, or door-knock visits to the suburb. Under the Privacy Act and associated marketing legislation, you can request to be removed from their list. The request can be verbal during the call or in writing afterward. Reputable agents maintain clean opt-out records and will comply promptly. If an agent continues to contact you after a clear opt-out request, that is a separate and more serious issue that you can escalate to the Office of Fair Trading.</p>

      <p>If you receive printed letters with handwritten-style addressing, those are usually mass-printed marketing pieces designed to feel personal. They are not letters from a single buyer to a single seller. Treat them as advertising and discard them unless they happen to be from an agent you would consider engaging anyway.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Treat unsolicited approaches as low-cost optionality. Occasionally one will lead to a genuinely good outcome. Most are routine prospecting and can be politely declined within sixty seconds. The risk is not that you decline a real opportunity; the risk is that you engage too readily with a prospecting call, get drawn into an appraisal you did not need, and end up agreeing to a campaign on terms that do not suit you.</p>

      <p>Use the contact as data about the agent and the local market, not as a commitment to engage. If the agent is genuinely active in your suburb and presents themselves well on the call, save their details for when you do decide to sell. If the agent's questions during the conversation reveal them to be generic and unfamiliar with your specific street and price range, that is information too. The conversation costs you nothing and tells you who is doing the work in your area.</p>

      <p>If a real offer ever arrives in writing, treat it as one data point in a wider decision. Compare it against comparable sales, take a second opinion from an agent of your choosing, and consider whether a short off-market exposure period would surface competing offers. Almost always, the answer to "should I take this offer" is a function of market context, not the agent's pitch.</p>

